-This presents a more subtle difficulty than the one we encountered with air. Consider what these equations of condition tell us about the relationship between light and ordinary matter—that is, between the velocity with which luminous vibrations propagate and the material velocities along which our ordinary mechanical forces carry us. If light travels through a real medium at a fixed speed, then the forces between particles must adjust as that speed increases. For ordinary mechanics show us that forces may change much more rapidly with an altered distance, and that light propagates through an elastic medium at a point speed. This means there should be a definite relationship between the velocity of light and the speed of propagation of ordinary matter. Yet the apparatus reveals no such relationship. Consider an analogy from sound and the velocity at which sound waves can be transmitted through air. If air is rarefied, the vibrations of air compress it somewhat, making it a conductor. The velocity of sound in any direction is therefore modified by this resistance. Similarly, light travels through an elastic medium—the luminiferous aether—at a speed that depends on its velocity in the particular medium, and with this speed, the forces and velocities of all material particles should adjust in the same proportion. This is a remarkable independence. If the aether makes a compact with ordinary matter as a plenum, as some mechanical theories suppose, then the speed of light should vary directly with that of ordinary matter, and the interference pattern should depend only on the ratio of luminous to opaque propagation. However, the apparatus shows no such variation. The expected mathematical relationship cannot be even an approximation, for the very possibility of such an agreement requires that the speed of light c should depend only upon the speed of propagation of ordinary matter A, B, and D. This is not merely a matter of physics, but an impossibility in nature.</think>

\\\\\\\When light travels through a real medium at a fixed speed, the forces between vibrating particles and the speed of propagation of ordinary matter should vary as the squares of these two velocities. If the speed of light is less than the speed of ordinary matter, then the electric forces and velocities will adjust their proportion, but only as the inverse square of that speed. This follows from the principle that the speed of light is a function of the luminous velocity in the medium, rather than being a pure mathematical property of that medium.</think>

\\\\\\When light travels through a real medium at a fixed speed, the relative but varying speed of vibrating particles and the velocity of light depend only on the inverse square relationship. The actual, finite speed of light c represents an arbitrary function of the intrinsic speed of wave propagation in the medium, rather than being a pure mathematical property of that medium.}
